ristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Maud de Hercy was born in 1328, in Grove, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Hugh de Grove Hercy, was 28 and her mother, Alicia, was 23. She had at least 1 son with Alexander de Mering. She died in 1378, in Meering, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 50."},"et":{"1328–1378":"1328–1378","1325–Male":"1325–Surnud","1345–1399":"1345–1399","1300–1367":"1300–1367","1305–1340":"1305–1340","1305":"1305","1325":"1325","1367":"1367","1378":"1378","1345":"1345","1300":"1300","1399":"1399","ABT 1345":"umbes 1345","1340":"1340","1328":"1328","about 1340":"umbes 1340","Grove, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Grove, Nottinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Mering Manor, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom":"Meering, Nottinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Nottingham, Nottinghamshire, England":"Nottingham, Nottinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Over Peover, Cheshire, England":"Over Peover, Cheshire, England","England, United Kingdom":"Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1